english:
  title: Record of the Andong Medicinal Clinic
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the autumn of the ninth month of the year Ding-Wei under the Zhi-Zheng reign, appointments came down for officials to guard Andong Prefecture. The prefect chosen was Hong Baek-jeong, current Minister of State, selected from among the Xuanning nobility. The magistrate was Jung Muk, former prefect of Jang-heung, selected from the office of Inspector-General. Both men took their leave at court and departed. In the early dawn of the tenth day of the tenth month of that year, the magistrate arrived first at the administrative hall, performed the proper rites, and facing the palace, expressed his gratitude for the royal favor. He then greeted the prefect in the courtyard. The prefect too performed the rites with equal reverence. After stepping back to receive the obeisance of the local clerks, the ceremonies concluded. The elders of the region congratulated one another on receiving capable men, and henceforth no command went unexecuted.

    When spring came in the second month of the following year, the two officials said to each other: "Heaven's vital force now unfolds, and all living things begin their growth. Consulting the seasonal ordinances, human welfare takes precedence. We must therefore prepare against sudden illness, nurture the life-force throughout the body, and preserve the great harmony. In this, medicine and healing have their purpose, and hot springs and bathing offer their aid. Why should we not give these priority?"

    They then searched for vacant ground, but found no suitable place until they discovered the old abandoned site of the defunct Law Ministry, where its foundation still remained. There they erected a building and named it the Medicinal Clinic, thereby honoring its essential purpose. Three rooms on the eastern side were designated for bathing, three rooms on the western side for the dispensing of medicines, and a central hall of greater height for receiving royal envoys. Travelers passing east and west could thus receive aid in their hour of need—a consideration not to be underestimated.

    Moreover, this region being the most remote and its people the most simple, many lack knowledge of proper remedies and hygiene. When noxious vapors strike them, misfortune often follows as a common occurrence. Yet Hong Baek-jeong championed this enterprise from above, while Magistrate Jung responded with equal zeal below. With half the effort expended, the full results have been achieved, and Andong shall forever benefit from their virtue. Such deeds merit recording.

    As the saying goes: "If one cannot become a great minister, let one become a good physician." Truly, the art of healing is of no small importance. Now Hong Baek-jeong applies such wisdom in serving the state, while Jung steadily advances toward greater responsibility. The efficacy of medicines and healing shall not end with Andong alone. Ah, how can one measure the extent of such blessing reaching to distant places?
  footnotes:
    - The Zhi-Zheng reign refers to the era of the Mongol Yuan Dynasty (1341-1368). Ding-Wei corresponds to 1367.
    - The phrase 'not to become a great minister, but rather a good physician' reflects a Confucian ideal valuing both statecraft and the healing arts as noble pursuits.
    - The 'vital force' (榮衛/영위) refers to the concept in traditional Chinese medicine of qi circulating through the body to maintain health and harmony.
